              font-weight: 500;
              margin-top: 2px !important;">What is the nudge theory?</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.longandshort.com/email/images/ls-jan-27-3.png" alt="What is the Lorenz curve?" href="https://www.longandshort.com" />
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000"> 
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">Nudge theory is a behavioral economics concept developed by Richard Thaler and Cass Sunstein. It suggests that subtle changes in how choices are presented can influence people’s decisions without restricting their freedom of choice.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">
          For example, automatically enrolling employees in retirement savings plans while allowing them to opt out significantly increases participation rates compared to requiring them to opt in. Another example is placing healthy foods at eye level in cafeterias to encourage healthier eating habits.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">Nudges have been widely applied in public health, finance, and environmental conservation. For instance, defaulting consumers to paperless billing reduces paper waste, while energy companies providing comparison reports on neighbors’ usage encourage households to conserve energy.
         </p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
